<LP>
   JAPAN AND THE U.S. completed a broad accord designed to
reduce their trade imbalance. Japan promised to spend more on
public works, toughen antitrust policies and streamline its
distribution system. The U.S. pledged to balance its budget,
improve worker training and boost research spending. The pact
got a cool reaction from some legislators, economists and
business people.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid is letting Minolta sell a Polaroid instant camera
to U.S. customers under a Minolta brand name. The highly
unusual marketing move reflects Polaroid's sluggish sales.
   ---
   Crude oil inventories are at an eight-year high, raising
the prospect of tumbling petroleum prices if OPEC doesn't
rein in production soon. Persian Gulf producers have been
cutting their third-quarter contract prices.
   ---
   Budget negotiators are talking increasingly about raising
taxes on Social Security benefits or reducing the program's
cost-of-living raises.
   ---
   The earnings outlook for the second quarter is largely
positive, despite some recent negative surprises, analysts
and money managers say. This is good news for investors with
broadly diversified stock portfolios.
   ---
   Lotus's copyright on the 1-2-3 program was infringed by
Paperback Software International in its VP Planner, a federal
judge ruled. The decision could foreshadow similar verdicts
in other software disputes.
   ---
   Apple Computer has dropped plans for an initial public
offering by its Claris software unit and intends to fold the
business back into the parent firm, industry executives say.
   ---
   A Mobil affiliate won clearance from the Nigerian
government to proceed with the $1 billion development of a
rich offshore petroleum field.
   ---
   Bond prices rose as investors reacted to brisk demand for
the latest Treasury note offering. The stock market also
gained, boosting the Dow Jones Industrial Average 16.58
points to 2878.71. The dollar was mixed.
   ---
   Venezuela reached an agreement with its major bank
creditors that includes provisions for new loans and for
cutting back old credits and the interest payments due on
them.
   ---
   Pathe's $1.31 billion bid to buy MGM/UA appeared in
jeopardy after Pathe said it reached an impasse with Time
Warner over financing. Pathe said it will seek other sources
of funding, and continue talking to Time.
   ---
   Manufacturers Hanover plans to take a substantial
second-quarter charge linked to its cost-cutting plan. The
banking concern also is placing more than $150 million of
loans to Trump on nonperforming status.
   ---
   AT&amp;T will cut long-distance prices an average of 2.2%, or
more than $300 million a year, starting Sunday.
   ---
   Soybean planting covered 58 million acres this year, the
government estimated, cutting its previous figure by 1.4
million acres. Some analysts expect soybean prices to climb
today.
   ---
   A group of insurers is developing a computer network to
improve communications with independent agents. Critics are
skeptical about the system's benefit to consumers.
   ---
